text.text:
In our experience, birthday meals fit into two main categories: the boozy, we're all in this together, long tables of rowdiness; and the slightly more memorable, slightly pricier, intimate affairs. We've given you plenty of options for the first kind already (see link below) but what about the romantic dinners for you and boo, the close family dinners with your parents or the gathering of the circle within your inner circle. 

This lot are prime for a small affair — the music isn't too loud, you've room to breathe and space to think. These are the kind of spots where the quality of experience matches the quality of conversation.
Click for... Birthday Dinners that Won't Break the Bank

action.name: Birthday Dinners That Won't Break the Bank

tip.text:
Any self-respecting ‘Restaurants to Visit’ hitlist is gonna have the name Noble Rot somewhere on it, including ours. Discreetly tucked down Lamb’s Conduit Street in Bloomsbury, this is the golden egg of evening haunts: a cosy, laid-back wine bar and restaurant suitable for the informal and formal; group dines or intimate meals; quick drinks or long, leisurely gorges.

It’s about great French wine (and lots of it), great British food and great schmoozy ambience: where you’ll roll in for a glass of £4 wine at 7pm, before its magic takes hold and you end up downstairs in the rustic bistro-style restaurant at a quarter to midnight, suitably merry and full bellied. Let the amiable waiters take care of your wining needs because the list is extensive; and if hunger strikes (and your budget allows) head mouth first into bits like lamb saddle, braised Cornish turbot and roast guinea fowl. This is how it’s done.

text.text: From the duo behind wine and lifestyle magazine of the same name, comes a laid-back wine bar & restaurant - Noble Rot. This snug wood-panelled haven serves up a seasonal menu of French meets British fare all expertly paired with the finest of wine recommendations.

tip.text:
Unless you take your time machine over to Paris, you're not finding a place like Le QuecumBar anywhere else. This is an intimate, mad little den dedicated to live Gypsy Swing, and the legendary guitarist Django Reinhardt. The music is amazing, the wine is flowing, and there's a classic French brasserie menu to get through as well. If you're after something a little different, hightail it down here.

Sundays and Mondays are ticketed concert nights showcasing some of the best Gypsy Swing players around. Grab tickets on their site.

tip.text:
Portland does the relaxed fine dining thing to a T. The food is about as beautiful and delicate as it could possibly be but the service is easy, friendly and there isn't a tablecloth in sight. Each parcel of flavour is seasonal, inventive, and just the right balance of rich and sweet. Words can't even describe how it made us feel so we choreographed an interpretive dance instead...

The menu is brief but strong. Bring all your money though cause those crispy chicken skins, with liver parfait, candied walnuts & muscat grapes will not pay for themselves - but what do you expect when there's a Michelin star in the game? The dessert menu even comes with careful drinks pairings. You can't have an apricot & almond tart with burnt honey ice-cream without Pink Moscato now can you?

tip.text:
Islington has plenty of good eateries and the Italian, Trullo is definitely one of them. The theme here seems to be simple but well done - the decor isn't over the top but it creates a nice environment that's perfect for shmoozing or to take the parents to. The food is in a similar vein: simple, seasonal Italian dishes on a smallish menu that changes regularly. Fish, meat and pasta are their hallmarks.

The pasta is made fresh and was probably the highlight when we went. In particular, the Pappardelle with beef shin ragu was goddamn excellent and is good as either a starter or a main. We'd also suggest tackling the Almond and Pear tart for a dessert. A really nice spot to go for a meal — get a load of dishes to share but be careful not to stack up too big a bill.

text.text: Islington has plenty of good eateries and Trullo is definitely up there with the best. The theme here seems to be simple but well done - the decor isn't too over the top. The food is in a similar vein: simple, seasonal Italian dishes on a smallish menu that changes regularly. There's a reason this is a cult classic and it has a lot to do with the tasty, tasty ragu.

tip.text:
This little bistro is about as French as you can get, with black and white checkerboard floors, proper bistro style tables and chairs lined up out front (for Parisian style people watching), and gorgeous French doors all the way along the front. 10 is the magic number here: they have 10 cases of tasty and unusual reds, whites and rosés on rotation and they work around those.

Written in scrawled writing on the blackboard, the menu changes daily and complements the vino on offer. Edible gems include the likes of a smoked duck breast salad with whatever seasonal veg is available. Food is simple and unpretentious; vibes are intimate but still bustly; and the wine menu is an adventure. It can get busy, so make sure to book yourself a spot.

text.text: This little bistro is about as French as you can get, with black and white chequered floors, proper bistro style tables and chairs lined up out front - for Parisian style people watching. 10 is the magic number here: they have 10 cases of tasty and unusual reds, whites and rosés on rotation; and a changing seasonal menu that complements the vino pretty darn well.

tip.text:
The third venue from the Old Spike Roastery lot, Aside is salivate central. Much as we wanted to stand by the kitchen door and watch each dish come out we weren't allowed. All joking aside, the menu really is summin'. It's small, seasonal and well curated, like a boutique festival. You can never be sure what's on the cards for your evening but think smoked eel croquettes, burrata with fennel and peach, or cod with mushrooms and corn. And the odd tasty curveball - goat curry?

They do a mighty good brunch 'ere too. We had a rustic and wholesome full English to make any farmhouse kitchen proud. Maybe you should make the time to get to know this little nugget, with an ice cold martini in hand of course.

tip.text:
The Palomar is a like a long-lost Israeli friend - they'll pull you in, do a shot with you, tell you some off-colour jokes and feed you until you're sent home on a stretcher. While this poky little Soho restaurant isn't big on space, it's massive on hospitality - saddle up to the marble counter, which looks into the buzzy open kitchen, and prepare to be dazzled as the chefs and hosts chat with you whilst they do their thing (a thing which we happen to be huge fans of).

The food is all about innovative small plates with the spirit of Levantine cuisine at their heart, and it works best when you really get involved - tear off a bit of yeast-y, warm kubaneh (bread), for example, and dunk it deep into creamy tahini. The menu changes frequently, but you can always expect belly-warming, moreish flavours that lull you into an ordering spree - and before you can say 'shalom', you've racked up a pretty hearty bill. It was all worth it though, right?

text.text: Want to know what dining the Israeli way is like? The Palomar pulls you in, feeds you, jokes with you, does a shot with you, then has you leave feeling more upbeat than when you walked in. We definitely recommend sitting at the bar to eat, with the chefs spending half the time cooking, the other half throwing out the banter and wanting to drink with you.

tip.text:
If you know BAO - one of the most worthwhile queues in Soho - you'll know to expect good things from their fine dining venture. They're poshing things up with interiors that hark back to the luxury dining rooms of 1930s Taiwan - think dark wood booths, ceiling fans, pastel seating and perfectly styled staff. There's even a tea booth serving pots of delicate teas you brew and pour yourself.

Have a dabble in the beautiful cocktails then prepare for the tricky task of choosing from the food menu which covers the mountainous regions of Taiwan and its capital, Taipei. You'll see classic dishes like the fish of the day marinated in fermented bean curd chilli or their street food Shengjian bao dumplings. We were blown away by all sorts of textures we had never tried before, but the stand out dish was a tiny salad of tomatoes and smoked eel - smokey, spicy, sour and umami all at once.

Mini ballers can grab the dumpling tasting menu for £29; and big ballers can hire out the Mahjong games room for dinner and games. Good old Shu!

text.text: Xu isn't a restaurant it's a full blown experience. From the pastel decor and the staff's outfits, to the tea ceremony and exotic food, it takes fine dining to a whole new level of beauty. Delve into the likes of the fish of the day marinated in fermented bean curd chilli with grilled bone vinegar sauce, or grab the dumpling tasting menu for a measly £29.

tip.text:
Nealty tucked away in Flat Iron Square (foodie hub extraordinaire), is the unassuming Lupins. All around voices boom, crowds crowd and bodies squash - but not in here. Like your quietly clever, hard working younger brother, Lupins subtly borrows from other countries' cuisines (we got a few Mexican hints on our visit), and carefully puts together a concise but laaavely menu of seasonal British small plates.

Sit at the counter and watch the pros plate up dainty versions of Cornish crab, roast pigeon and polenta crusted anchovies; or grab a table but the window upstairs - it can get pretty hot up in here. If you're at all human you will find it hard not to fall for the burrata, with pea, fennel, mint gremolata and lardo. Finish with a ver British lemon posset or share a plate of Neal's Yard cheese for quiet patriotism. And the wine list? They were excited about, we were excited about it, so get on it.

tip.text:
Venetian slang for a glass of wine, Ombra is a cosy slice of the laid-back Venetian life amidst the hustle of Mare Street. And when we say Venetian life, we're not talking about the thousands of people squished into the Piazza San Marco. We mean a friendly neighbourhood joint perfect for sipping on something Campari-infused, tucking into some decadent pasta whilst chewing the fat between mouthfuls.

With chef Mitshel cooking away in the raised kitchen at the back, this is a simple affair with no frills or gimmicks: the short menu features snacks, antipasti, pasta and a couple of mains, depending on what's fresh. Each dish seems pretty carefully put together, and we particularly rate the cuttlefish, trompette de la mort and sorrel. If you're not into eating, we also spotted plenty of sorts sharing a cocktail or two and having DMCs.

From Tuesday to Friday they do a lunch menu (12pm-3pm) at £12 for a bowl of pasta and a glass of wine.

tip.text:
When you have three successful restaurants in the Clapham area and are looking for another, it's easiest to switch up one of the existing ones. That's what chef Robin Gill quickly worked out - and so The Manor became Sorella - an Italian of the fine dining variety.

Elements of its predecessor remain, those heavy plates, the striped back aesthetic and the ingredient-led cooking. The selection is relatively small (as is the rule with seasonal menus) and sticks to the traditional cicchetti, antipasti, primi, secondi, dolci format. The Italians love their endless courses. If you've a burning hole in your pocket then plump for the tasting menu, at £45 it gives you a tidy selection of flavours.

Look out for the likes of cep gnocchi with wild mushrooms, crab linguine and a classy-as-hell malted barley affogato to finish. Cocktails are gently Italian too, negronis make an appearance, of course, but seasonal options are worth a look in. We'll have that quince bellini, thank you sir.

text.text: Sorella is an Italian of the fine dining variety from the man behind The Dairy (just around the corner, mind). It's a stripped back, heavy plates, set menu kind of place where food feels important. Look out for the likes of cep gnocchi with wild mushrooms, crab linguine and a classy-as-hell malted barley affogato to finish.

tip.text:
Leroy sits in a genre of restaurant that London certainly isn't short of. The wine is of the natural variety, the bread artisanal and the produce local, seasonal and of the highest quality. But there's something - a little indescribable something - that it does differently. Sure it has a Michelin star, but also it just gets us.

Is it the decor perhaps, which treads the line between smart and stylish so neatly? Or the extensive vinyl collection, neatly slotted above an open kitchen that kicks out palpable sex appeal? Whatever it is, it's a hella convivial place, serving quality European wine, classy bar snacks and some of the tastiest small plates in town. Expect the veggies to be bang on season; offal or seafood to be handled with care; and sauces to ooze the kind of savoury delights that require much sourdough mopping.

text.text: For a smart dinner with a difference Leroy always delivers. We can't get enough of its smart, stylish but low key decor, extensive vinyl collection, quality (and natural) European wine, classy bar snacks and some of the tastiest small plates in town. Order extra sourdough and get to mopping up all those dreamy sauces.

tip.text:
Noizé is a beautiful restaurant. From the big, bright windows; to the red banquet seating and subtle, ornate tiling; all the way down to the hand-stitched napkins, everything here feels meticulously thought out to create a relaxed air of informal formality.

And the menu supports this feeling entirely. Nothing is intimidating, over-the-top or over explained, but when your food arrives you get the joy of piecing together what you’re looking at - ‘ah, the peas are a puree, the Jersey royals in mash form, and the walnut sauce a foam’, or surprise additions like kaffir lime with the raw scallop and celery. It’s classic French dining, but with just enough inventiveness to keep you on your toes.

And the drinks? We tried a couple of cocktails which were both fantastic (shout out to the amber negroni) and a range of wines that were all sublime. While nothing here is cheap, nothing is particularly expensive either, and relative to the quality of the experience and what you might be forking out at similar establishments, it’s a veritable steal. This feels like the kind of place we’d like to come for all our birthdays, with a quiet confidence to it that makes us want to tell all our friends about - but you’ll do.

tip.text:
After a slam dunk in Balham, Alex, Arthur and Tasos the 'bros' behind Brother Marcus decided to set up in Angel with a slightly more upmarket version of their brunch, cocktails and small plates triptych. Cooking up his Greek family flavours, Tasos lays on a spread of delicate-but-punchy small plates - full of colour and personality. A dish of marinated sardines here, a few hunks of buttermilk spiced chicken with muhammara (red pepper dip) there, and finally, with some perfectly tendered lamb chops he had us in the palm of his hand.

Placed on the mighty cute, pedestrianised Camden Passage - Brother Marcus' outdoor tables and window seats are prime for people and dog watching alike. Pair that with a tidy list of cocktails (Cherry Bomb, we will never forget you) and you've got the makings of a quality first date.

Expect lamb chops to be perfectly tendered, cocktails to be punchy and people watching opportunities to be strong from the cosy window seats.

tip.text:
With Selin Kiazim and Laura Christie (the Oklava team) behind this one, we know it's a goodie. The menu takes inspiration from Kyseri, the Turkish province famed for its pastas. Think manti - the little dumpling-like pasta filled with spiced beef and sour cherry, and served with yoghurt sauce, tomato-chilli butter and pine nuts.

Expect plenty of fresh fish and some magic veg dishes too - put us down for the slow-cooked celeriac, with preserved mandarin and sunflower seeds please. There's wine to be drunk (Turkish and Cypriot wines available by the glass and - our favourite vino container - the carafe), a couple of outside tables to be had; along with some striking orange seats and the Mayfair price tag.

text.text: Sister restaurant to Oklava, Kyseri takes menu inspiration from the Turkish province of Kayseri. Expect plenty of Turkish pasta, fresh fish and some magic veg dishes too. There's wine to be drunk (Turkish and Cypriot), a couple of booth tables to be nabbed... It's a real plush experience for the taking.
